s=3D"bl-page__col-center order-2 col-lg-9 col-xl-9"><article class=3D"bl-pa=
ge__content"><h1 id=3D"statistical-power">Statistical Power</h1><p>There ar=
e four interrelated components that influence the conclusions you might rea=
ch from a statistical test in a research project. The logic of statistical =
inference with respect to these components is often difficult to understand=
 and explain. This paper attempts to clarify the four components and descri=
be their interrelationships.</p><p>The four components are:</p><ul><li><str=
ong>sample size</strong> is the number of units (e.g. people) accessible to=
 the study;</li><li><strong>effect size</strong> is the salience of the tre=
atment relative to the noise in measurement;</li><li><strong>alpha level</s=
trong> (<code>=CE=B1</code>, or significance level) is the odds that the ob=
served result is due to chance;</li><li><strong>statistical power</strong> =
(<code>1=E2=88=92=CE=B2</code>) is the odds that you will observe a treatme=
nt effect when it occurs.</li></ul><p>Given values for any three of these c=
omponents, it is possible to compute the value of the fourth. For instance,=
 you might want to determine what a reasonable sample size would be for a s=
tudy. If you could make reasonable estimates of the effect size, alpha leve=
l and power, it would be simple to compute (or, more likely, look up in a t=
able) the sample size.</p><p>Some of these components will be more manipula=
ble than others depending on the circumstances of the project. For example,=
 if the project is an evaluation of an educational program or counseling pr=
ogram with a specific number of available consumers, the sample size is set=
 or predetermined. Or, if the drug dosage in a program has to be small due =
to its potential negative side effects, the effect size may consequently be=
 small. The goal is to achieve a balance of the four components that allows=
 the maximum level of power to detect an effect if one exists, given progra=
mmatic, logistical or financial constraints on the other components.</p><p>=
<a href=3D"https://conjointly.com/kb/statistical-power/#the-statistical-inf=
erence-decision-matrix">The Statistical Inference Decision Matrix</a> shows=
 the basic decision matrix involved in a statistical conclusion. All statis=
tical conclusions involve constructing <a href=3D"https://conjointly.com/kb=
/hypotheses-explained/">two mutually exclusive hypotheses</a>, termed the n=
ull (labeled H<sub>0</sub>) and alternative (labeled H<sub>1</sub>) hypothe=
sis. Together, the hypotheses describe all possible outcomes with respect t=
o the inference. The central decision involves determining which hypothesis=
 to accept and which to reject. For instance, in the typical case, the null=
 hypothesis might be:</p><blockquote><p><strong>H<sub>0</sub>:</strong> Pro=
gram Effect =3D 0</p></blockquote><p>while the alternative might be</p><blo=
ckquote><p><strong>H<sub>1</sub>:</strong> Program Effect =E2=89=A0 0</p></=
blockquote><p>The null hypothesis is so termed because it usually refers to=
 the =E2=80=9Cno difference=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cno effect=E2=80=9D case. U=
sually in social research we expect that our treatments and programs will m=
ake a difference. So, typically, our theory is described in the alternative=
 hypothesis.</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://conjointly.com/kb/statistical-pow=
er/#the-statistical-inference-decision-matrix">table below</a> is a complex=
 figure that you should take some time studying. First, look at the header =
row (the shaded area). This row depicts reality =E2=80=93 whether there rea=
lly is a program effect, difference, or gain. Of course, the problem is tha=
t you never know for sure what is really happening (unless you=E2=80=99re G=
od). Nevertheless, because we have set up mutually exclusive hypotheses, on=
e must be right and one must be wrong. Therefore, consider this the view fr=
om God=E2=80=99s position, knowing which hypothesis is correct. The first c=
olumn of the 2=C3=972 table shows the case where our program does not have =
an effect; the second column shows where it does have an effect or make a d=
ifference.</p><p>The left header column describes the world we mortals live=
 in. Regardless of what=E2=80=99s true, we have to make decisions about whi=
ch of our hypotheses is correct. This header column describes the two decis=
ions we can reach =E2=80=93 that our program had no effect (the first row o=
f the 2=C3=972 table) or that it did have an effect (the second row).</p><p=
>Now, let=E2=80=99s examine the cells of the 2=C3=972 table. Each cell show=
s the Greek symbol for that cell. Notice that the columns sum to <code>1</c=
ode> (i.e. <code>=CE=B1 + (1-=CE=B1) =3D 1</code> and <code>=CE=B2 + (1-=CE=
=B2) =3D 1</code>). Why can we sum down the columns, but not across the row=
s? Because if one column is true, the other is irrelevant =E2=80=93 if the =
program has a real effect (the right column) it can=E2=80=99t at the same t=
ime not have one. Therefore, the odds or probabilities have to sum to <code=
>1</code> for each column because the two rows in each column describe the =
only possible decisions (accept or reject the null/alternative) for each po=
ssible reality.</p><p>Below the Greek symbol is a typical value for that ce=
ll. You should especially note the values in the bottom two cells. The valu=
e of <code>=CE=B1</code> is typically set at <code>.05</code> in the social=
 sciences. A newer, but growing, tradition is to try to achieve a statistic=
al power of at least <code>.80</code>. Below the typical values is the name=
 typically given for that cell (in caps). If you haven=E2=80=99t already, y=
ou should note that two of the cells describe errors =E2=80=93 you reach th=
e wrong conclusion =E2=80=93 and in the other two you reach the correct con=
clusion. Sometimes it=E2=80=99s hard to remember which error is Type I and =
which is Type II. If you keep in mind that Type I is the same as the a or s=
ignificance level, it might help you to remember that it is the odds of fin=
ding a difference or effect by chance alone. People are more likely to be s=
usceptible to a Type I error, because they almost always want to conclude t=
hat their program works. If they find a statistical effect, they tend to ad=
vertise it loudly. On the other hand, people probably check more thoroughly=
 for Type II errors because when you find that the program was not demonstr=
ably effective, you immediately start looking for why (in this case, you mi=
ght hope to show that you had low power and high <code>=CE=B2</code> =E2=80=
=93 that the odds of saying there was no treatment effect even when there w=
as were too high). Following the capitalized common name are several differ=
ent ways of describing the value of each cell, one in terms of outcomes and=
 one in terms of theory-testing. In italics, we give an example of how to e=
xpress the numerical value in words.</p><p>To better understand the strange=
 relationships between the two columns, think about what happens if you wan=
t to increase your power in a study. As you increase power, you increase th=
e chances that you are going to find an effect if it=E2=80=99s there (wind =
up in the bottom row). But, if you increase the chances that you wind up in=
 the bottom row, you must at the same time be increasing the chances of mak=
ing a Type I error! Although we can=E2=80=99t sum to <code>1</code> across =
rows, there is clearly a relationship. Since we usually want high power <em=
>and</em> low Type I Error, you should be able to appreciate that we have a=
 built-in tension here.</p><h2 id=3D"the-statistical-inference-decision-mat=
rix">The Statistical Inference Decision Matrix</h2><figure class=3D"img-cen=
ter-full"><picture><img alt=3D"Statistical Inference Decision Matrix" title=
=3D"Statistical Inference Decision Matrix" src=3D"https://conjointly.com/im=
g/statistical-inference-decision-matrix.svg" width=3D"1000" height=3D"400">=
</picture></figure><p>We often talk about alpha (<code>=CE=B1</code>) and b=
eta (<code>=CE=B2</code>) using the language of =E2=80=9Chigher=E2=80=9D an=
d =E2=80=9Clower.=E2=80=9D For instance, we might talk about the advantages=
 of a higher or lower =CE=B1-level in a study. You have to be careful about=
 interpreting the meaning of these terms. When we talk about <em>higher</em=
> =CE=B1-levels, we mean that we are <em>increasing</em> the chance of a Ty=
pe I Error. Therefore, a <em>lower</em> =CE=B1-level actually means that yo=
u are conducting a <em>more rigorous</em> test. With all of this in mind, l=
et=E2=80=99s consider a few common associations evident in the table. You s=
hould convince yourself of the following:</p><ul><li>the lower the <code>=
=CE=B1</code>, the lower the power; the higher the =CE=B1, the higher the p=
ower.</li><li>the lower the <code>=CE=B1</code>, the less likely it is that=
 you will make a Type I Error (i.e. reject the null when it=E2=80=99s true)=
.</li><li>the lower the <code>=CE=B1</code>, the more =E2=80=9Crigorous=E2=
=80=9D the test.</li><li>an <code>=CE=B1</code> of <code>.01</code> (compar=
ed with <code>.05</code> or <code>.10</code>) means the researcher is being=
 relatively careful, s/he is only willing to risk being wrong 1 in a 100 ti=
mes in rejecting the null when it=E2=80=99s true (i.e. saying there=E2=80=
=99s an effect when there really isn=E2=80=99t).</li><li>an <code>=CE=B1</c=
ode> of <code>.01</code> (compared with <code>.05</code> or <code>.10</code=
>) limits one=E2=80=99s chances of ending up in the bottom row, of concludi=
ng that the program has an effect. This means that both your statistical po=
wer and the chances of making a Type I Error are lower.</li><li>an <code>=
=CE=B1</code> of <code>.01</code> means you have a <code>99%</code> chance =
of saying there is no difference when there in fact is no difference (being=
 in the upper left box).</li><li>increasing <code>=CE=B1</code> (e.g. from =
<code>.01</code> to <code>.05</code> or <code>.10</code>) increases the cha=
nces of making a Type I Error (i.e. saying there is a difference when there=
 is not), decreases the chances of making a Type II Error (i.e. saying ther=
e is no difference when there is) and decreases the rigor of the test.</li>=
<li>increasing <code>=CE=B1</code> (e.g. from <code>.01</code> to <code>.05=
</code> or <code>.10</code>) increases power because one will be rejecting =
the null more often (i.e. accepting the alternative) and, consequently, whe=
n the alternative is true, there is a greater chance of accepting it (i.e. =
power).</li></ul></article><div class=3D"next-button d-flex justify-content=
